subSubSection.paragraph: Diagnosis. This species is clearly distinct from all congeners in pronotal edges deeply lobate, combined with regularly nodulose alternate intervals of elytra and lack of interfacetal setae.

Head transverse with a distinct median raised area on frons; supraorbital carina raised, strongly indented with a narrow posterior portion distinctly raised above eye; supra-antennal carina slightly raised, edge indented; angulate protrusion between antennal insertion and eye, visible in lateral view; eyes protruding, without interfacetal setae; antennal insertion ventral, just below the edge of supra-antennal carina; antennae 11 -segmented with a distinct 3 - segmented club; antennomere I rounded, 1.5 times as long as II; II and III subcylindrical; III distinctly wider, about as long as II; IV–VIII very short and simple; IX–XI transverse to form a rather loose club.

Pronotum transverse (pronotal length/width: 0.65–0.73 ), narrower than elytra at base, about as wide or slightly wider at anterior angles, without prominent median process; margins distinctly lobate; maximum width at anterior angles, with one wide angulate lobe directed anteriorly and two small, pointed lobes, one at middle and one at posterior angle; sculpture of pronotum as in
Fig. 2
g. Two posterior pronotal lobes well separated from the anterior, much larger lobe, but not always clearly separated from each other.

Elytra about twice as long as wide (elytral length/width: 1.92–2 ), with lateral margins straight and smooth; relatively low tubercles on 3 rd, 5 th and 7 th intervals, numerous ( 7–10 per interval) and subequal in size.

Distribution and habitat occurrence. SE South Australia , Victoria, Tasmania, New South Wales , Australian Capital Territory and SE Queensland (
Fig. 9
a); open forest with single records from mulga (Bulla Bulla tank in NSW ), Cypress Pine forest (Manna S.F. in NSW ) and Pine plantation (under pine bark in Stromlo Forest, A.C.T.).
